1
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:26,161
<i>What do you want me to say, Bruce?</i>

2
00:01:26,200 --> 00:01:30,922
He broke into our offices this morning,
accessed our files, our computers.

3
00:01:31,560 --> 00:01:33,289
<i>Do we know what?</i>

4
00:01:33,360 --> 00:01:35,010
Well, we can assume everything.

5
00:01:35,240 --> 00:01:36,844
This is a major liability.

6
00:01:37,080 --> 00:01:38,206
You're telling me.

7
00:01:38,280 --> 00:01:40,851
Renaldo, now!
<i>Vamos, vamos!</i> Let's go!

8
00:01:40,920 --> 00:01:42,365
<i>Okay, okay!</i>

9
00:01:43,120 --> 00:01:44,281
Does the army know who he is?

10
00:01:44,640 --> 00:01:47,291
Yeah. Francisco Francis.

11
00:01:51,120 --> 00:01:54,488
Come on, come on.
Just keep walking, keep quiet, okay?

12
00:01:54,800 --> 00:01:57,451
- Renaldo!
- Mama!

13
00:01:57,520 --> 00:01:58,885
No, Renaldo!

14
00:01:59,600 --> 00:02:00,601
Renaldo!

15
00:02:19,080 --> 00:02:20,923
She's dead, Renaldo.
Come on, come on, come on!

16
00:02:26,760 --> 00:02:29,923
Come on, come on, get inside!

17
00:02:38,080 --> 00:02:39,127
Let me out!

18
00:02:43,280 --> 00:02:45,328
No, no, no, no!

19
00:02:45,400 --> 00:02:47,289
I don't care what General Aguila
is doing right now!

20
00:02:47,360 --> 00:02:49,488
I want you to put him on the phone, now!

21
00:02:49,520 --> 00:02:51,841
Let me out right now! Let me out!

22
00:02:51,920 --> 00:02:53,490
It's Tony Green from ClearBec!

23
00:02:53,720 --> 00:02:55,290
Let me out of this car!

24
00:03:26,960 --> 00:03:28,291
Jesus Christ...

25
00:03:36,160 --> 00:03:38,367
<i>Did you ever hear about
the great transformation?</i>

26
00:03:38,440 --> 00:03:40,807
<i>Yeah, I think... What was that again?</i>

27
00:03:40,880 --> 00:03:43,929
<i>It started about 300 years ago in England.</i>

28
00:03:45,040 --> 00:03:48,487
<i>With the turning of public lands
into private property.</i>

29
00:03:48,520 --> 00:03:52,241
<i>It changed the way we think,
the way we view time</i>

30
00:03:52,280 --> 00:03:54,726
<i>and land and water and even people,</i>

31
00:03:54,800 --> 00:03:56,723
<i>turned them into units,</i>

32
00:03:57,120 --> 00:04:00,681
<i>commodities to be bought and sold
and therefore exploited.</i>

33
00:04:00,760 --> 00:04:02,762
<i>Yeah, but what is bought and
sold is constant.</i>

34
00:04:02,840 --> 00:04:04,126
<i>That's never gonna change.</i>

35
00:04:04,160 --> 00:04:06,160
You know what, Sarah?
That is absolutely incorrect.

36
00:04:06,320 --> 00:04:09,688
<i>Society needs to approve of the things
to be turned into commodities</i>

37
00:04:09,760 --> 00:04:11,285
<i>before they can be bought or sold.</i>

38
00:04:11,440 --> 00:04:15,126
People can be bought or sold, correct?
And that did happen.

39
00:04:15,200 --> 00:04:18,409
As horrific and diabolical
as that may sound, it's a fact.

40
00:04:18,640 --> 00:04:21,484
<i>Yeah, and still slavery
happens in some countries today.</i>

41
00:04:21,600 --> 00:04:23,250
<i>Regrettably true.</i>

42
00:04:23,480 --> 00:04:26,927
<i>But why is it that in Western society,
we no longer buy and sell people?</i>

43
00:04:27,000 --> 00:04:30,368
<i>Because it's immoral
and it's wrong in all aspects.</i>

44
00:04:31,080 --> 00:04:33,606
<i>Well, is it wrong to sell water?</i>

45
00:04:35,160 --> 00:04:37,367
<i>What about air?
Would it be wrong to sell air?</i>

46
00:04:37,440 --> 00:04:40,364
<i>Air! Come on, man!
I mean, you can't sell air.</i>

47
00:04:40,400 --> 00:04:41,731
<i>No?</i>

48
00:04:41,800 --> 00:04:43,564
<i>Well, what if you can't afford it?</i>

49
00:04:43,640 --> 00:04:47,611
<i>There's lots of people all around the world
that can't afford much water.</i>

50
00:04:47,640 --> 00:04:49,290
<i>- And what happens?
- I don't know.</i>

51
00:04:49,480 --> 00:04:50,720
<i>They die.</i>

52
00:04:50,800 --> 00:04:52,768
<i>Is it so farfetched, Sarah?</i>

53
00:04:52,840 --> 00:04:56,162
You can sell water,
but you can't sell air? Think about it.

54
00:04:56,240 --> 00:04:58,208
I'll take the next caller.

55
00:04:58,280 --> 00:05:00,681
Hello, this is Jack Begosian,
you're on the air.

56
00:05:00,760 --> 00:05:02,171
<i>The name's Charlie.</i>

57
00:05:02,240 --> 00:05:03,480
Hello, Charlie. Good morning.

58
00:05:03,520 --> 00:05:07,491
<i>Morning. I want to know
when we're gonna talk about the real truth.</i>

59
00:05:07,560 --> 00:05:09,085
What truth is that, Charlie?

60
00:05:09,160 --> 00:05:11,561
<i>About the aliens
taking over the White House.</i>

61
00:05:11,600 --> 00:05:13,648
The aliens taking over
the White House?

62
00:05:13,720 --> 00:05:15,961
<i>You know you know it, Jack.</i>

63
00:05:18,000 --> 00:05:19,923
You mean illegal aliens, Charlie.

64
00:05:20,000 --> 00:05:21,923
<i>No, you're making light.</i>

65
00:05:22,000 --> 00:05:25,721
<i>Extra-terrestrial beings
are a real threat to our way of life, Jack.</i>

66
00:05:25,800 --> 00:05:29,088
Only if you exchange
bodily fluids with them, Charlie.

67
00:05:29,160 --> 00:05:30,810
I'm not, are you?

68
00:05:30,880 --> 00:05:32,041
<i>No.</i>

69
00:05:32,080 --> 00:05:34,242
Then we're doing our part.
Thanks for calling.

70
00:05:35,440 --> 00:05:36,521
Last call.

71
00:05:36,600 --> 00:05:38,568
Hi, this is Jack Begosian,
you're on the air.

72
00:05:38,640 --> 00:05:40,244
<i>Hey, man,
it's Van from Oakland.</i>

73
00:05:40,320 --> 00:05:43,210
Hello, Van from Oakland, California.
Thanks for the call.

74
00:05:43,280 --> 00:05:44,805
<i>- A question, Jack.</i>
- Yes?

75
00:05:44,880 --> 00:05:46,530
<i>Why did you quit?</i>

76
00:05:46,960 --> 00:05:48,644
Why did I quit what?

77
00:05:48,720 --> 00:05:51,405
<i>The agency, dude. Everybody knows.</i>

78
00:05:53,360 --> 00:05:54,850
Why did I quit?

79
00:05:54,920 --> 00:05:56,285
<i>Yeah.</i>

80
00:05:58,680 --> 00:06:04,847
<i>Well, Van, when you
can't effect change from within,</i>

81
00:06:05,840 --> 00:06:10,164
I mean positive change, you have an
obligation if you're at all conscious,

82
00:06:10,240 --> 00:06:12,527
to get out and try other things.

83
00:06:12,680 --> 00:06:13,727
That's what I'm doing.

84
00:06:13,800 --> 00:06:16,724
<i>Other things?
You mean, like ways to effect change?</i>

85
00:06:16,760 --> 00:06:17,841
Yes.

86
00:06:18,520 --> 00:06:21,444
<i>You think people want to hear the truth,
man, but they don't.</i>

87
00:06:21,520 --> 00:06:24,569
<i>They want sound bites,
celebrity gossip, scandal, you know.</i>

88
00:06:25,800 --> 00:06:27,131
<i>This is true.</i>

89
00:06:27,200 --> 00:06:29,885
<i>The news doesn't have
to be truthful anymore, just entertaining.</i>

90
00:06:29,960 --> 00:06:30,961
<i>Nice!</i>

91
00:06:31,040 --> 00:06:34,044
<i>You know, our values are eroding,
our morals...</i>

92
00:06:34,120 --> 00:06:36,168
<i>What are we doing here, man?</i>

93
00:06:36,240 --> 00:06:39,164
<i>The real question is,
what are we really after?</i>

94
00:06:39,240 --> 00:06:42,084
<i>Is there some ultimate end,</i>

95
00:06:42,160 --> 00:06:46,210
<i>or are we just into some sort of endless
pursuit of nothing more than pleasure?</i>

96
00:06:46,280 --> 00:06:47,361
<i>What do you think?</i>

97
00:06:47,440 --> 00:06:50,125
<i>I believe there's meaning
to it, to our lives.</i>

98
00:06:50,160 --> 00:06:51,321
<i>That's what I believe.</i>

99
00:06:51,360 --> 00:06:52,646
<i>Meaning? Like what?</i>

100
00:06:52,720 --> 00:06:54,165
<i>I haven't learned that answer yet.</i>

101
00:06:54,200 --> 00:06:57,124
<i>Well, keep up the good work
until they shut you down, dude.</i>

102
00:06:57,200 --> 00:06:58,884
<i>They're not gonna shut me down, Van.</i>

103
00:06:58,960 --> 00:07:01,440
<i>Yeah, they will.
The CIA is suing you, right?</i>

104
00:07:02,440 --> 00:07:03,930
Rumors.

105
00:07:04,840 --> 00:07:08,401
And I hate to break it to you,
but the CIA does not sue.

106
00:07:08,600 --> 00:07:10,170
<i>What do they do, then?</i>

107
00:07:10,240 --> 00:07:12,686
<i>They have several other options.</i>

108
00:07:13,480 --> 00:07:14,845
<i>But I'd welcome my day in court.</i>

109
00:07:14,920 --> 00:07:17,605
<i>Do you think they would? Think about it.</i>

110
00:07:17,680 --> 00:07:19,444
<i>Thanks for the call.</i>

111
00:07:22,440 --> 00:07:24,124
One last thought.

112
00:07:27,200 --> 00:07:29,965
Sometimes it seems
like a bleak picture.

113
00:07:30,840 --> 00:07:34,811
But it really isn't because
the basic nature of mankind is good.

114
00:07:36,400 --> 00:07:39,404
<i>And if you don't believe me,
go on the subway,</i>

115
00:07:39,480 --> 00:07:43,451
<i>on the bus at rush hour and take
a good look around, look at the people...</i>

116
00:07:43,520 --> 00:07:46,285
Black, brown, red, yellow, white.

117
00:07:47,960 --> 00:07:51,169
<i>They're all coming home
from an honest day's work.</i>

118
00:07:52,280 --> 00:07:54,681
And they don't do it for the money

119
00:07:54,760 --> 00:07:57,525
because their jobs are
paying them very little.

120
00:07:59,480 --> 00:08:01,448
<i>But they do it for their families.</i>

121
00:08:03,920 --> 00:08:06,321
They do it for the ones they love.

122
00:08:07,400 --> 00:08:11,246
<i>And you can see it,
and you can feel it.</i>

123
00:08:12,240 --> 00:08:15,244
<i>You can see it in their tiredness,
in their resignation,</i>

124
00:08:15,320 --> 00:08:18,051
<i>and you can feel it
in their commitment,</i>

125
00:08:18,480 --> 00:08:20,881
<i>their commitment to their families.</i>

126
00:08:22,040 --> 00:08:24,566
<i>This is Jack Begosian. Good night.</i>

127
00:08:24,640 --> 00:08:26,165
<i>Good morning.</i>

128
00:09:08,600 --> 00:09:12,889
And can you make reservations
for Clare van Huysen and I,

129
00:09:12,960 --> 00:09:15,645
at that new French restaurant for two?
You know the one.

130
00:09:15,720 --> 00:09:17,210
<i>At 2:00?</i>

131
00:09:17,240 --> 00:09:19,811
No, for two at 1:00.

132
00:09:19,920 --> 00:09:23,720
<i>But the ribbon-cutting ceremony
at the hospital won't be over by then.</i>

133
00:09:23,800 --> 00:09:25,689
- It won't?
<i>- No.</i>

134
00:09:26,280 --> 00:09:27,770
<i>I'll make it 2:00 for two.</i>

135
00:09:27,840 --> 00:09:29,842
Okay, perfect. Thank you.

136
00:09:32,720 --> 00:09:34,404
<i>Yes, ClearBec is very pleased</i>

137
00:09:34,480 --> 00:09:37,882
<i>we've funded this new wing dedicated
to children's cancer research.</i>

138
00:09:37,960 --> 00:09:39,200
<i>And in addition to this wing,</i>

139
00:09:39,280 --> 00:09:43,569
<i>ClearBec has also funded
a hospice for the out-of-town parents,</i>

140
00:09:43,640 --> 00:09:46,120
<i>which will allow them
extended stays with the children</i>

141
00:09:46,200 --> 00:09:47,611
<i>during ongoing treatments.</i>

142
00:09:47,640 --> 00:09:51,406
<i>So, thank you, everyone.
To our future, the children.</i>

143
00:09:53,120 --> 00:09:55,248
Miss Swinton,
how much is ClearBec paying

144
00:09:55,320 --> 00:09:58,449
to the South African government
to privatize their water system?

145
00:09:58,600 --> 00:09:59,965
Miss Swinton!

146
00:10:00,040 --> 00:10:02,771
Does your company still intend to sign
this deal despite the mass protests?

147
00:10:02,840 --> 00:10:04,171
Miss Swinton. Miss Swinton, stop!

148
00:10:05,520 --> 00:10:06,601
Back!

149
00:10:10,000 --> 00:10:13,891
Your company killed my family,
killed my entire town,

150
00:10:13,960 --> 00:10:15,530
poisoned them,
then shot the survivors.

151
00:10:16,760 --> 00:10:18,205
You will remember them.

152
00:10:25,920 --> 00:10:28,446
<i>I presume
I have your attention now, Miss Swinton.</i>

153
00:10:28,520 --> 00:10:31,171
<i>My country
and many others in South America</i>

154
00:10:31,240 --> 00:10:33,163
<i>are in the war for water rights.</i>

155
00:10:33,240 --> 00:10:34,480
<i>Who knows of this?</i>

156
00:10:34,560 --> 00:10:38,042
<i>Few, as it is not happening
in New Orleans or New York.</i>

157
00:10:39,080 --> 00:10:41,811
<i>The noise you hear is gunfire.</i>

158
00:10:41,880 --> 00:10:46,090
<i>Children, women and men are being
gunned down outside Tayca, Ecuador.</i>

159
00:10:46,560 --> 00:10:48,767
<i>I recorded it, saw it.</i>

160
00:10:50,400 --> 00:10:54,724
<i>Inagua, a local subsidiary of ClearBec,
your family's company,</i>

161
00:10:54,800 --> 00:10:59,442
<i>installed a water purification system
for Tayca and the surrounding area.</i>

162
00:10:59,520 --> 00:11:02,763
<i>The system did not purify.
Just the opposite.</i>

163
00:11:03,920 --> 00:11:06,400
<i>A very bad form of typhus
emerged in the town.</i>

164
00:11:12,320 --> 00:11:15,483
<i>Francisco Francis broke into
the Inagua office.</i>

165
00:11:15,560 --> 00:11:18,609
<i>ClearBec's own report stated what
was happening and how they were involved.</i>

166
00:11:27,880 --> 00:11:30,087
You can't help them.
We have to get out now.

167
00:11:31,240 --> 00:11:33,481
There is always
something you can do.

168
00:11:34,680 --> 00:11:36,330
The dead are the dead.

169
00:11:36,760 --> 00:11:38,444
We can help
the ones that are left.

170
00:11:38,520 --> 00:11:40,682
But look at what
you have in your arms.

171
00:11:41,680 --> 00:11:44,763
Francisco, I can't live
without you again.

172
00:11:46,440 --> 00:11:50,240
We're together forever.

173
00:11:50,320 --> 00:11:51,401
Forever.

174
00:12:04,240 --> 00:12:06,925
<i>The army, ClearBec's partner in Ecuador,</i>

175
00:12:07,000 --> 00:12:09,890
<i>moved into my town
and quarantined the area.</i>

176
00:12:12,600 --> 00:12:13,931
<i>They had orders to find Francis</i>

177
00:12:14,000 --> 00:12:17,243
<i>and kill any residents
that were trying to get out.</i>

178
00:12:42,280 --> 00:12:44,681
<i>No one knew what to do
with the sick and the dying.</i>

179
00:12:44,960 --> 00:12:47,440
<i>Then the soldiers began to get sick.</i>

180
00:12:48,360 --> 00:12:50,647
<i>They began to execute everyone.</i>

181
00:14:12,400 --> 00:14:14,641
<i>Question, Jack. Why'd you quit?</i>

182
00:14:19,040 --> 00:14:20,760
I thought I answered that question already.

183
00:14:21,320 --> 00:14:23,687
<i>Yeah, but I want the real reason.</i>

184
00:14:32,280 --> 00:14:34,521
<i>I stopped believing in lies</i>

185
00:14:36,760 --> 00:14:38,649
<i>including my own.</i>

186
00:14:48,640 --> 00:14:50,768
<i>ClearBec has provided you
quality water products</i>

187
00:14:50,840 --> 00:14:53,002
<i>for over 50 years.</i>

188
00:14:53,080 --> 00:14:57,244
<i>ClearBec stands for
integrity, value, quality.</i>

189
00:14:57,720 --> 00:15:02,248
<i>Your body is over 70% water, over 70%.</i>

190
00:15:02,720 --> 00:15:04,563
<i>You deserve the best water possible.</i>

191
00:15:17,320 --> 00:15:19,766
<i>The kid was my assistant last summer.</i>

192
00:15:20,560 --> 00:15:22,767
Okay? How the hell
did he get to Toronto?

193
00:15:23,800 --> 00:15:26,371
Whatever. He just blew his brains out
in front of my sister

194
00:15:26,440 --> 00:15:27,771
at a press conference, Tony.

195
00:15:27,960 --> 00:15:32,682
Okay, Bruce. You should never have
authorized the use of force here.

196
00:15:33,000 --> 00:15:34,286
- I didn't.
<i>- Then who did?</i>

197
00:15:34,400 --> 00:15:37,290
General Aguila.
He said he had no choice.

198
00:15:37,320 --> 00:15:39,687
That's bullshit! I saw it happen.

199
00:15:39,720 --> 00:15:41,085
It was murder, Bruce.

200
00:15:41,720 --> 00:15:44,485
Aguila is a general
for the Ecuadorian army.

201
00:15:44,560 --> 00:15:46,847
<i>He's not an officer
or an employee of ClearBec.</i>

202
00:15:47,200 --> 00:15:49,441
We are not guilty of anything.

203
00:15:49,800 --> 00:15:52,849
I am saddened and disgusted
as to what happened down there,

204
00:15:52,920 --> 00:15:54,126
<i>but we are not to blame.</i>

205
00:15:54,200 --> 00:15:55,361
Yeah, so, then, what?

206
00:15:55,640 --> 00:15:57,001
- Damage control.
- Damage control?

207
00:15:57,040 --> 00:15:58,087
Yes.

208
00:15:58,360 --> 00:16:01,011
Do you understand
that it was more than just a few villagers?

209
00:16:01,400 --> 00:16:03,209
<i>It was hundreds of people, Bruce!</i>

210
00:16:03,280 --> 00:16:06,443
Even though ClearBec is innocent,
we can't let our South African partners

211
00:16:06,520 --> 00:16:08,807
<i>find out what really happened
down there, all right?</i>

212
00:16:09,080 --> 00:16:10,525
It's best for the company.

213
00:16:11,880 --> 00:16:13,325
Tony, I'll call you back.

214
00:16:13,360 --> 00:16:14,885
<i>Call me back!</i>

215
00:16:16,640 --> 00:16:18,051
How are you?

216
00:16:18,560 --> 00:16:19,891
Jesus, are you all right?

217
00:16:22,400 --> 00:16:23,925
What happened in Ecuador?

218
00:16:25,960 --> 00:16:27,803
I am so sorry you had to see that.

219
00:16:29,520 --> 00:16:32,524
We pulled a file on that kid.
He was a nutcase.

220
00:16:33,000 --> 00:16:36,163
He was working for
an anti-government rag magazine.

221
00:16:36,240 --> 00:16:38,322
He infiltrated our Ecuadorian offices.

222
00:16:38,720 --> 00:16:40,848
I listened to a tape he left for me.

223
00:16:41,200 --> 00:16:42,406
A tape?

224
00:16:42,720 --> 00:16:44,688
What did we do down there?

225
00:16:46,600 --> 00:16:48,360
We have interests in
Ecuador, you know that.

226
00:16:49,160 --> 00:16:50,764
- Interests?
- Yes.

227
00:16:51,040 --> 00:16:52,690
A boy doesn't

228
00:16:54,320 --> 00:16:56,368
blow his head off over interests.

229
00:16:57,160 --> 00:16:58,650
We're an international company.

230
00:16:59,040 --> 00:17:02,806
We can't possibly
make everyone happy all the time.

231
00:17:02,840 --> 00:17:04,001
It gets complicated.

232
00:17:04,040 --> 00:17:05,929
It's best if you don't get involved.

233
00:17:06,520 --> 00:17:08,124
Don't get involved in our own company?

234
00:17:09,480 --> 00:17:13,041
The company that our father built.

235
00:17:13,720 --> 00:17:16,849
Morgan, you do lunches,
you do ribbon-cuttings,

236
00:17:17,360 --> 00:17:20,170
you do fund-raisers,
you do bad marriages.

237
00:17:25,600 --> 00:17:26,726
Wow.

238
00:17:32,240 --> 00:17:33,321
I'm sorry.

239
00:17:34,760 --> 00:17:36,489
You should go home.

240
00:17:36,560 --> 00:17:38,801
Clean yourself up, okay?

241
00:17:40,680 --> 00:17:41,841
Sorry.

242
00:17:57,880 --> 00:18:00,201
What happened in Ecuador
needs to be contained, Doug.

243
00:18:00,280 --> 00:18:02,521
Believe me, Bruce, I know that.

244
00:18:02,880 --> 00:18:06,327
None of these events
can be traced back to ClearBec at any cost.

245
00:18:06,400 --> 00:18:07,561
Right.

246
00:18:07,800 --> 00:18:10,246
Now, Tony was shaken up,
but I think he will be all right.

247
00:18:10,280 --> 00:18:13,250
But from what I just heard,

248
00:18:13,720 --> 00:18:16,121
I'm afraid your sister might be a problem.

249
00:18:16,200 --> 00:18:17,361
What are you suggesting?

250
00:18:17,440 --> 00:18:19,727
Morgan needs to be deflected.

251
00:18:21,560 --> 00:18:24,211
Goldman Brothers, line two.
You gotta take it.

252
00:18:29,200 --> 00:18:30,531
Bobby, how are you?

253
00:18:30,600 --> 00:18:32,602
How the hell
do you expect me to get this closed?

254
00:18:32,680 --> 00:18:34,170
Have you seen what's
coming up about ClearBec

255
00:18:34,200 --> 00:18:35,725
since that kid blew his brains out?

256
00:18:36,200 --> 00:18:37,964
That kid was a nut-job, Robert.

257
00:18:38,240 --> 00:18:41,767
The press is all over it, Bruce.
It's completely killing the financing.

258
00:18:42,040 --> 00:18:45,283
We have to close by the end of next week.
Otherwise, South Africa pulls out.

259
00:18:45,360 --> 00:18:46,771
That's the scheduled close.

260
00:18:47,040 --> 00:18:49,850
You want to close by the end of next week,
then our fees just doubled.

261
00:18:50,120 --> 00:18:52,160
Does that mean we're not playing squash
on Saturday?

262
00:18:52,320 --> 00:18:53,685
<i>You'll have a new deal memo in an hour.</i>

263
00:18:53,720 --> 00:18:55,404
<i>I want it signed and executed back today.</i>

264
00:18:55,480 --> 00:18:56,606
Fine.

265
00:18:56,680 --> 00:18:58,648
<i>And if anything else like
this happens, Bruce,</i>

266
00:18:59,360 --> 00:19:01,124
we're out of this deal.

267
00:19:05,040 --> 00:19:06,280
Bye-bye.

268
00:19:31,880 --> 00:19:34,360
<i>I have no idea how many were killed.</i>

269
00:19:34,440 --> 00:19:35,680
<i>Hundreds.</i>

270
00:19:40,200 --> 00:19:42,726
<i>They burned the bodies, the evidence.</i>

271
00:19:44,800 --> 00:19:46,450
<i>But some got away.</i>

272
00:19:51,040 --> 00:19:55,364
<i>I did, before they infected people
who survived.</i>

273
00:20:00,200 --> 00:20:03,886
<i>And I pray that
Francisco Francis made it out.</i>

274
00:20:05,760 --> 00:20:07,808
<i>Francis is a great man.</i>

275
00:20:07,880 --> 00:20:10,281
<i>They jailed him, beat
him, tried to kill him.</i>

276
00:20:10,360 --> 00:20:12,249
<i>But he keeps rising up!</i>

277
00:20:15,880 --> 00:20:20,408
<i>He is witness to what happened.
He will tell the truth.</i>

278
00:20:30,040 --> 00:20:32,646
<i>If he is alive, you must help him.</i>

279
00:20:32,720 --> 00:20:34,722
<i>May God have mercy on you
if you don't.</i>

280
00:20:41,000 --> 00:20:43,970
<i>Jason, I made you
your favorite breakfast.</i>

281
00:20:44,560 --> 00:20:47,201
If you're not gonna eat it,
then you might as well go to your room.

282
00:20:52,600 --> 00:20:53,726
What's going on?

283
00:20:54,160 --> 00:20:55,605
I don't know.

284
00:20:56,600 --> 00:20:59,080
He's not eating, just staring at the clock.

285
00:20:59,680 --> 00:21:01,205
What's wrong with the clock?

286
00:21:01,280 --> 00:21:02,566
Nothing.

287
00:21:04,000 --> 00:21:06,128
Since when is he not eating?

288
00:21:07,280 --> 00:21:08,441
A couple of days.

289
00:21:08,840 --> 00:21:10,080
How come you haven't told me?

290
00:21:10,920 --> 00:21:12,684
I've been trying to.

291
00:21:17,880 --> 00:21:20,804
You don't know, he's so
frustrating, I mean...

292
00:21:21,680 --> 00:21:22,966
Karen...

293
00:21:26,720 --> 00:21:29,371
You were the one
who wanted to move out here off the grid.

294
00:21:30,880 --> 00:21:32,086
I know.

295
00:21:32,800 --> 00:21:34,802
And deal with his issues.

296
00:21:36,440 --> 00:21:38,124
I can't do it by myself.

297
00:21:41,080 --> 00:21:42,320
You are not by yourself.

298
00:21:42,720 --> 00:21:44,051
Yes, I am.

299
00:21:46,560 --> 00:21:49,484
You're here, but you're not here.

300
00:21:56,440 --> 00:22:01,207
I feel it, and Jason sure as
hell feels it more than I do.

301
00:22:02,120 --> 00:22:03,360
I know.

302
00:22:06,480 --> 00:22:08,801
You need to spend some time with him.

303
00:22:12,360 --> 00:22:13,850
Quality time.

304
00:22:21,360 --> 00:22:22,521
Jack...

305
00:22:25,560 --> 00:22:27,210
Just be with him.

306
00:22:28,440 --> 00:22:30,408
Spend more time with your son.

307
00:22:31,120 --> 00:22:32,360
Please.

308
00:22:56,480 --> 00:22:57,925
<i>Bruce, listen to me.</i>

309
00:22:57,960 --> 00:22:59,724
<i>I've been thinking about this, okay?</i>

310
00:22:59,760 --> 00:23:02,764
<i>Please, we gotta help these people.
We can't just leave them.</i>

311
00:23:03,240 --> 00:23:04,924
<i>We have to call in World Health.</i>

312
00:23:05,440 --> 00:23:07,647
<i>They can contain the typhus.</i>

313
00:23:07,720 --> 00:23:10,166
Tony, if we call in the WHO,

314
00:23:10,240 --> 00:23:11,890
that's like sending out a press release

315
00:23:11,960 --> 00:23:14,167
saying that ClearBec
caused the typhus outbreak.

316
00:23:14,440 --> 00:23:16,124
If that happens,
the government of South Africa

317
00:23:16,200 --> 00:23:17,600
will pull out of the deal for sure.

318
00:23:17,680 --> 00:23:21,730
You think the South African deal
justifies what Aguila did?

319
00:23:22,080 --> 00:23:25,050
No, I don't, but he said
it was a disaster beyond imagination,

320
00:23:25,120 --> 00:23:27,680
that what he did was the only way
to contain the typhus outbreak.

321
00:23:27,720 --> 00:23:29,404
And you believe him, right?

322
00:23:29,560 --> 00:23:32,370
We have a company to run.
I have shareholders to report to.

323
00:23:32,640 --> 00:23:34,290
<i>Now we have to do the right thing.</i>

324
00:23:34,360 --> 00:23:36,680
What the hell happened
to our filtration system down there?

325
00:23:37,280 --> 00:23:40,602
The river flooded, okay?
That's what happened.

326
00:23:40,800 --> 00:23:42,370
But we've tested for that extensively.

327
00:23:42,600 --> 00:23:46,889
The sewers backed up
and then rats were infesting the town.

328
00:23:47,440 --> 00:23:50,046
The market will crucify us
if this ever gets out.

329
00:23:50,320 --> 00:23:52,766
I don't know, man. I don't know anymore.

330
00:23:52,840 --> 00:23:55,366
I just... You tell me,
what's the official story?

331
00:23:55,880 --> 00:23:57,006
The truth.

332
00:23:59,960 --> 00:24:02,964
He broke into our filtration plant
and sabotaged the system.

333
00:24:03,040 --> 00:24:05,122
That's what caused the typhus outbreak.

334
00:24:05,200 --> 00:24:06,725
The army came in to apprehend him,

335
00:24:06,800 --> 00:24:09,610
Francis and his men fired back,
the army returned fire.

336
00:24:09,680 --> 00:24:11,523
There were casualties, end of story.

337
00:24:12,000 --> 00:24:13,411
<i>Have they gotten to Francis yet?</i>

338
00:24:13,440 --> 00:24:15,522
Yeah, he's hiding up in
the mountains somewhere.

339
00:24:15,920 --> 00:24:17,524
All right, Tony.

340
00:24:17,600 --> 00:24:19,728
You do whatever you can
to help those people down there.

341
00:24:19,800 --> 00:24:21,882
But please keep a lid on it.

342
00:24:39,600 --> 00:24:41,807
You wanna go help me
stack some firewood?

343
00:24:46,000 --> 00:24:47,365
Come on.

344
00:24:51,200 --> 00:24:53,567
I heard you crying last night, Mommy.

345
00:24:53,640 --> 00:24:55,404
Why were you crying?

346
00:24:55,880 --> 00:25:00,807
Because Mommy saw something
that made her feel sad.

347
00:25:01,320 --> 00:25:04,130
<i>My sister called me.
She said she's being followed.</i>

348
00:25:04,200 --> 00:25:07,647
She's been online trying to figure out
what really happened in Ecuador.

349
00:25:07,760 --> 00:25:09,922
- You tapped into her computer?
- Yes.

350
00:25:10,000 --> 00:25:11,968
I never authorized you to do that.

351
00:25:12,040 --> 00:25:15,408
Well, I apologize, Bruce,
I didn't think you'd object.

352
00:25:15,480 --> 00:25:17,767
She's on our system
and we have responsibilities.

353
00:25:17,800 --> 00:25:19,768
We both have to answer
to the Board of Directors.

354
00:25:19,800 --> 00:25:22,724
This is the flavor of the week.
She'll lose interest in a second.

355
00:25:22,800 --> 00:25:25,929
I don't agree.
I think this really has her going.

356
00:25:26,640 --> 00:25:29,644
She made an appointment
with Tom Delmonte about this.

357
00:25:29,680 --> 00:25:31,250
- Her lawyer?
- Yes.

358
00:25:32,120 --> 00:25:33,645
I think we should call in Torrance.

359
00:25:34,680 --> 00:25:35,841
I don't know.

360
00:25:36,320 --> 00:25:40,530
There's a lot of things in this situation
which could use special handling.

361
00:25:40,600 --> 00:25:42,523
We should call in Tor now.

362
00:25:47,480 --> 00:25:49,209
<i>Did you listen to the tape?</i>

363
00:25:49,280 --> 00:25:50,611
<i>Yes.</i>

364
00:25:50,680 --> 00:25:54,162
<i>Were you able to make arrangements
to send money to the boy's family?</i>

365
00:25:54,360 --> 00:25:57,170
I'm sorry, we couldn't locate
any relatives at all.

366
00:25:59,640 --> 00:26:02,484
I need to find out
what happened down there.

367
00:26:03,000 --> 00:26:06,607
ClearBec does have legitimate
interests in South America, Morgan.

368
00:26:06,680 --> 00:26:10,924
Look, the boy stuck a gun into his mouth
and blew his brains out in front of me.

369
00:26:11,000 --> 00:26:14,322
I think something ugly is being covered up.

370
00:26:14,840 --> 00:26:17,764
And I think that you
should not get involved.

371
00:26:19,920 --> 00:26:22,366
Can you find me someone
to send down there?

372
00:26:22,400 --> 00:26:24,289
You're serious?

373
00:26:29,040 --> 00:26:32,328
There's one of our investigators
in Washington that might be helpful.

374
00:26:32,400 --> 00:26:33,640
I could speak to him.

375
00:26:33,720 --> 00:26:35,688
- I'll get back to you.
- Thank you.

376
00:26:45,960 --> 00:26:48,964
It's Calder. We have a situation.

377
00:26:49,840 --> 00:26:51,046
ID number?

378
00:26:52,720 --> 00:26:55,963
237418665.

379
00:26:57,120 --> 00:26:59,771
I understand your
South African deal's in jeopardy.

380
00:26:59,840 --> 00:27:01,968
<i>That's why I'm calling you.</i>

381
00:27:02,640 --> 00:27:04,120
Well, you should have called earlier.

382
00:27:04,840 --> 00:27:06,968
We have some problem areas.

383
00:27:07,480 --> 00:27:10,051
And I think Morgan Swinton
may be one of them.

384
00:27:12,200 --> 00:27:13,440
She and Bruce really close?

385
00:27:13,840 --> 00:27:16,047
Well, they're siblings,

386
00:27:16,120 --> 00:27:19,522
but if push comes to shove,
I imagine Bruce will do what he has to do.

387
00:27:21,880 --> 00:27:25,009
Send me what you have on this.
Send me everything.

388
00:27:25,080 --> 00:27:26,809
<i>I was in South America a long time,</i>

389
00:27:26,880 --> 00:27:29,167
I never saw anything like this.

390
00:27:29,240 --> 00:27:31,004
It's a serious mess.

391
00:27:31,600 --> 00:27:33,728
We have to make this disappear.

392
00:27:41,080 --> 00:27:42,570
Yeah?

393
00:27:42,840 --> 00:27:45,684
<i>Doing much these days, Jack?</i>

394
00:27:46,960 --> 00:27:48,007
Not really.

395
00:27:48,160 --> 00:27:50,731
Some civilian wants something checked
out in Ecuador, good money.

396
00:27:51,720 --> 00:27:52,881
You take it.

397
00:27:52,960 --> 00:27:54,561
<i>Still got a price on my head down there.</i>

398
00:27:55,200 --> 00:27:59,728
Take a flight, look around, fly back home,
file a report, pick up a nice check.

399
00:27:59,960 --> 00:28:01,610
What's the matter?

400
00:28:02,600 --> 00:28:04,602
- I don't think so.
<i>- You can't outrun it, Jack.</i>

401
00:28:05,400 --> 00:28:06,600
You ought to know that by now.

402
00:28:06,880 --> 00:28:08,723
I don't like you, Clive.

403
00:28:09,160 --> 00:28:11,120
No. You don't like anybody
who knows what you did.

404
00:28:11,240 --> 00:28:12,446
Come on, let's pick this up, come on.

405
00:28:12,520 --> 00:28:15,000
You forget it was for a good cause.

406
00:28:15,480 --> 00:28:17,642
It wasn't for a cause.
It was for vested interests.

407
00:28:18,720 --> 00:28:20,290
<i>Take the job.</i>

408
00:28:20,360 --> 00:28:21,486
I got a family now.

409
00:28:21,800 --> 00:28:22,801
You're marking time.

410
00:28:22,920 --> 00:28:25,161
I've already hung up, Clive...

411
00:29:42,800 --> 00:29:45,531
Hey, you're leaving earlier and earlier.

412
00:29:54,640 --> 00:29:55,846
I have a lot of work to do.

413
00:29:58,640 --> 00:30:00,847
I listen to your show every night, Jack.

414
00:30:02,440 --> 00:30:04,090
Do you know that?

415
00:30:04,240 --> 00:30:09,326
I lie in bed and I listen to it
until I fall asleep.

416
00:30:13,560 --> 00:30:16,131
It's the next best thing
to having you beside me.

417
00:30:18,560 --> 00:30:22,281
I'm always amazed
at how much you give to complete strangers.

418
00:30:24,320 --> 00:30:26,084
It's part of the show.

419
00:30:27,440 --> 00:30:29,920
I wish you'd bring more of the show home.

420
00:30:36,240 --> 00:30:37,924
What is it, Jack?

421
00:30:40,680 --> 00:30:42,682
What are you looking for?

422
00:30:46,360 --> 00:30:48,124
Like the show says.

423
00:30:49,920 --> 00:30:51,365
Yeah...

424
00:30:52,400 --> 00:30:54,562
Well, maybe the truth is right here.

425
00:30:58,040 --> 00:31:00,327
You were always
the smartest girl in the room.

426
00:31:04,480 --> 00:31:05,845
I gotta go.

427
00:31:10,200 --> 00:31:12,521
Jason ate a little bit with me today.

428
00:31:17,360 --> 00:31:19,010
Just a little bit.

429
00:31:26,440 --> 00:31:29,762
<i>I don't care what you say!
I think it was stupid.</i>

430
00:31:30,080 --> 00:31:31,605
I disagree. It wasn't stupid.

431
00:31:31,680 --> 00:31:34,809
It was an impassioned choice, a sacrifice.

432
00:31:34,880 --> 00:31:38,566
<i>My father always told me there is nothing
worth laying your life down for.</i>

433
00:31:39,400 --> 00:31:40,526
<i>I disagree.</i>

434
00:31:40,600 --> 00:31:42,240
<i>You don't know what you're talking about!</i>

435
00:31:42,480 --> 00:31:43,640
What is life without freedom?

436
00:31:43,680 --> 00:31:45,091
<i>You're still alive.</i>

437
00:31:46,520 --> 00:31:47,931
<i>Is freedom worth dying for?</i>

438
00:31:47,960 --> 00:31:49,291
<i>No, it is not!</i>

439
00:31:49,360 --> 00:31:51,124
That's the question.

440
00:31:51,400 --> 00:31:54,290
<i>This is Jack Begosian. Good night.</i>

441
00:31:54,360 --> 00:31:56,044
<i>And good morning.</i>

442
00:32:04,360 --> 00:32:05,566
Jack?

443
00:32:07,600 --> 00:32:09,125
Jack Begosian?

444
00:32:10,640 --> 00:32:11,687
Yes?

445
00:32:12,680 --> 00:32:14,444
I'm Morgan Swinton.

446
00:32:14,880 --> 00:32:16,803
Yes, I know. I saw you on the news.

447
00:32:18,120 --> 00:32:20,521
You have a moment?
I need to talk with you.

448
00:32:31,080 --> 00:32:32,809
<i>The village was quarantined
and many people,</i>

449
00:32:32,880 --> 00:32:37,010
<i>perhaps hundreds, died or were executed
for corporate protection.</i>

450
00:32:37,560 --> 00:32:39,085
ClearBec may be implicated.

451
00:32:39,640 --> 00:32:42,803
I need someone to go down there
and find out what happened.

452
00:32:42,880 --> 00:32:45,201
And you come highly recommended.

453
00:32:45,600 --> 00:32:49,400
I'm told you're very familiar
with that part of the world.

454
00:32:49,920 --> 00:32:51,445
I've already said no.

455
00:32:51,520 --> 00:32:53,329
And I'm asking you to reconsider.

456
00:32:55,880 --> 00:32:59,566
There may be survivors,
witnesses to what happened.

457
00:32:59,640 --> 00:33:01,483
If there are, I need you
to bring them back here.

458
00:33:01,560 --> 00:33:03,528
- And then what?
- I'll go public.

459
00:33:04,080 --> 00:33:06,080
I'll stop them from doing
that deal in South Africa

460
00:33:06,120 --> 00:33:10,125
because you know
what they'll do down there.

461
00:33:11,480 --> 00:33:12,686
Bleed it dry.

462
00:33:13,440 --> 00:33:16,091
<i>They'll be left trying to
suck an elephant through a straw.</i>

463
00:33:16,160 --> 00:33:18,322
<i>I'll pay you very well, Mr. Begosian.</i>

464
00:33:19,080 --> 00:33:21,128
Fifty thousand before
you travel down to Ecuador.

465
00:33:21,200 --> 00:33:24,807
If you come back
with witnesses, another 200,000.

466
00:33:26,120 --> 00:33:28,885
All expenses paid,
including private air travel.

467
00:33:31,120 --> 00:33:33,202
Wasn't your father
the founder of ClearBec?

468
00:33:34,960 --> 00:33:36,121
Yes.

469
00:33:36,280 --> 00:33:37,486
Then why are you doing this?

470
00:33:39,040 --> 00:33:42,010
My father taught me everything has a price,

471
00:33:42,080 --> 00:33:43,809
but not everything should be for sale.

472
00:33:46,880 --> 00:33:48,920
Ever seen a boy
blow his brains out in front of you?

473
00:33:51,760 --> 00:33:53,250
Unfortunately.

474
00:33:55,000 --> 00:33:57,162
ClearBec was a good company,
Mr. Begosian.

475
00:34:03,760 --> 00:34:05,649
Listen to this recording.

476
00:34:05,720 --> 00:34:09,725
It mentions a name, Francisco Francis.

477
00:34:13,120 --> 00:34:15,407
That name mean anything to you?

478
00:34:20,560 --> 00:34:23,450
<i>A very bad form of typhus
emerged in the town.</i>

479
00:34:23,520 --> 00:34:26,490
<i>Francisco Francis broke into
the Inagua office.</i>

480
00:34:26,560 --> 00:34:30,007
<i>ClearBec's own report stated what
